          "body": "Two brief warnings pivot the chapter toward the marginalized. Do not speak wisdom to a fool — he will despise it (23:9). Do not move the ancient boundary or enter the fields of the fatherless (23:10). The two warnings seem unrelated, but they share a logic: some relationships are structurally unequal, and the wise man must read that inequality correctly. The fool cannot receive wisdom; the fatherless cannot defend their property. The first warns against wasting wisdom on those who despise it (a pastoral principle); the second warns against exploiting those who have no human advocate. The deterrent in 23:11 is decisive: 'their Redeemer (go'el) is strong; He will plead their case against you.' God Himself functions as the orphan's kinsman-redeemer — the legal champion who takes up the case no human court will hear. This is one of the most significant theological statements in the chapter: YHWH enters the property dispute of the powerless as their personal legal advocate."
