          "title": "The father's deepest appeal (23:12-26)",
          "body": "The chapter's center is neither a warning nor a proverb cluster — it is a father's personal appeal to his son. Beginning in 23:12 with the command to 'apply your heart to discipline,' the sage moves through parental discipline (23:13-14), his own joy at a wise son (23:15-16), the theological anchor of the fear of the LORD (23:17-18), the command to avoid gluttons and drunkards (23:19-21), the honor due to parents (23:22), the call to buy truth (23:23), and the joy a righteous son brings to his parents (23:24-25). The climax is 23:26: 'Give me your heart, my son, and let your eyes delight in my ways.' The Hebrew is startling — the father does not say 'obey my commands' but 'give me your heart.' The appeal is for the son's inner person, not merely external compliance. Tim Keller notes that wisdom in Proverbs is always a matter of reordered loves, not merely corrected behaviors; 23:26 is the sharpest expression of that in the entire book. The father wants what the fool's wine and the miser's table also want — the son's heart. The question is who gets it."
