        "title": "The adulteress — a deep pit and a narrow well (23:27-28)",
        "range": "23:27-28",
        "excerpt": "For a harlot is a deep pit and an adulterous woman is a narrow well. Surely she lurks as a robber, and increases the faithless among men.",
        "body": "Two verses, two images, one argument. The harlot (zanah) is a 'deep pit' (shuchah amoq); the adulteress (nokhri, foreign/strange woman) is a 'narrow well' (beer tsar). Both images are architectural traps. The deep pit captures the suddenness and invisibility of the fall — you do not see it until you are in it. The narrow well captures the impossibility of self-rescue once you have fallen — its walls are too close to brace against for escape. Together they describe a trap that is easy to fall into and nearly impossible to exit from.\n\nThe nokhri ('foreign woman') of Proverbs is not primarily an ethnic designation — she is the woman who stands outside the covenant community and its sexual ethics, whose allure is precisely her otherness. She appears in Proverbs 2:16-19, 5:3-20, 6:24-35, and 7:1-27; she is the embodied anti-type to wisdom, whose house leads to Sheol (5:5; 7:27). In 23:28, her predatory nature is stated without metaphor: 'she lurks as a robber (cheteph).' The Hebrew cheteph is used of violent, ambush-style predation — this is not passive seduction but active hunting.\n\nThe communal consequence in 23:28b is often overlooked: 'she increases the faithless (bagad) among men.' Bagad means the treacherous, the covenant-breakers. Sexual unfaithfulness is not merely personal ruin — it multiplies the population of men who have broken their most fundamental covenant. The sage understands adultery as a social contagion, not merely a private sin. This aligns with Paul's warning in 1 Corinthians 6:18-20 and the structure of the seventh commandment's placement in the Decalogue as a social covenant, not merely a personal ethical rule.\n\nThe brevity of this section (only two verses) within the chapter's longer structure is itself a rhetorical choice. The extended wine poem that follows takes twenty-one lines to make its argument; the adulteress warning takes two. The implication is that the trap of the adulteress requires less elaboration than the trap of wine — perhaps because the fall into sexual sin is more obviously catastrophic, or perhaps because the father has already addressed it extensively in Proverbs 1-9 and assumes the son remembers."
